{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6048d3b7-13e7-4550-ae33-896e6d7c3be8","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n## 1. Lost Test History in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **default test-ID generation strategy**. IDs are now computed differently, so Azure DevOps sees every test as new. Fix by opting back into the legacy strategy in your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <TestIdGenerationStrategy>Legacy</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nOr accept the new IDs and let history rebuild over time.\n\n## 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is now a **class-level context** — it has no test-specific info because no individual test is running yet. Accessing `TestName` throws `InvalidOperationException`.\n\nYour code on line 13:\n```csharp\nvar testName = context.TestName; // throws in v4\n```\n\n**Fix:** Remove the `TestName` access from `ClassInit`, or move that logic into `[TestInitialize]` where a per-test context exists.\n\n## Other v4 Changes to Watch For\n\n| Area | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| `[DataRow]` | No longer performs implicit type conversions (e.g., `int` → `long` will fail) |\n| `[Timeout]` | Now applies to the test body only, not setup/cleanup |\n| `TestContext.Properties` | Read-only in class/assembly-level contexts |\n| Parallel execution | Default parallelism scope changed; review `[Parallelize]` settings |\n| `Assert.ThrowsException` | Generic overload now validates exact type (not derived) |\n| `[DeploymentItem]` | Paths resolved differently; verify if you use relative paths |\n\nWould you like me to patch `SetupTests.cs` to fix the `ClassInitialize` issue?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cc2d5e97-58ac-4bb5-b6a7-651c852f36d5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I can provide a comprehensive answer about MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me address both issues and highlight other things to watch out for.\n\n1. **Tests appearing as brand new (lost history in Azure DevOps)**: In MSTest v4, the default test ID generation strategy changed. Previously, test IDs were based on a legacy format; now they use a new stable ID format. Since Azure DevOps tracks test history by test ID, all tests appear \"new\" after upgrading. The fix is to set `<TestIdGenerationStrategy>` or use the `[TestId]` attribute approach.\n\n2. **TestContext.TestName in [ClassInitialize]**: In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is now a \"class-level\" context that doesn't have test-specific information. \n\nAccessing `TestName` will throw an `InvalidOperationException` because there's no individual test running at class initialization time — that method runs once for the entire class, not per test. Beyond these two issues, I should also mention that `DataRow` no longer performs implicit type conversions, `DeploymentItem` behavior has shifted, `TestContext.Properties` is read-only in certain contexts, assembly-level attributes work differently, timeout handling has changed, and parallel execution defaults may vary from what you're used to.","outputTokens":793,"requestId":"E3C9:127371:BF8200:DABA51:6A053F28"},"id":"7744044d-327f-4c60-9fbc-6d55c6b74403","timestamp":"2026-05-14T03:19:23.583Z","parentId":"8866967f-60e0-4799-b7f2-6ef0977a5e7b"}
